			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The idea has been brought up my many smart people here and I have been thinking about this for a while..  How to best make something like this work.
<br />

<br />

<br />
How can pets be made to scale properly as a 65 mage advances.  (and some balancing below that)?
<br />

<br />
How can pets become more valuable in a given situation?  
<br />

<br />
Those two questions are heavily asked.  Here is what I think.  Based in no small part from the community here.
<br />

<br />
First we would have to change the pet component.  
<br />

<br />
There would be three levels. / three new components  The components would could be called coalesced elements.  Lesser, normal, and greater  Could be just two.  Will let you guys decide that one.  
<br />

<br />
The lesser coalesced elements is used for the Conjurations, the 34 to 49 pets, and has 1 augment slot  (optional)
<br />

<br />
The coalesced elements is used for the vocarates, The 51 to 60 pets, and has 2 augment slots.
<br />

<br />
The Greater coalesced elements affect the planar pets 61+ and has three or 4 augment slots.  Three normal, and one time level Type 8.
<br />

<br />
They would be purchasable from the normal spell component vendors for an appropriate amount.  Malachite would no longer be used in summoning pets.
<br />

<br />
That sounds great but what do we do with those slots…  Glad you asked my friend.  Change some common and uncommon drops that are now vendor fodder to augments for pets.  Possibly add a spell or two in the 50’s to “summon” pet augments with minor abilities, and keep the better ones as drops.  That will provide the scaling of pets.
<br />

<br />
Example  Dust of mistmore in the LdoN Mistmore theme could add Bane Vs. Undead damage.  The amount would depend on what component it went into.  I’m thinking something like 2, 5 and 10.
<br />

<br />
Other drops would add different bane damage,  Elemental Damage. Atk, AC, HP,  even real procs.  
<br />

<br />
Yeah but now that we have the augment, and the component what do we do now.  That Arch Magus Gilmore that you have just sitting around will be used for that.  Simply pop in a component, and an augment and combine.  Repeat the process for adding more augments, Just like using the bird bath.  
<br />

<br />
Not here is something to warn you about.  While the components by themselves will stack, as will the augments.  Augmented components will not.  Why, There are to many variables.  
<br />

<br />
But Elawise, how do I know which one of my augmented components will be used?  Ahhh yes my friend, you are familiar with how food and drink works are you not.  Well the augmented components work exactly the same way.  The spell will use the first one it comes to, so make sure you have the component you want to use in the "front" of your inventory.  
<br />

<br />
Now for the Time level (Type <img src="images/smiles/icon_cool.gif" alt="Cool" border="0" /> slot.  Scaling time  J  A drop in time when inserted into a greater component would do things like add 1000+ atk, or 100 to Max Damage or AE immunity.  They would of course be uncommon to rare drop.  But then Their use us pretty uncommon.  If make the pet an asset to the raid.  If you think about overpowering the pet.  Remember only one Type 8 one can be used…  But think about it.  An 85 to 90 hitting pet hitting max every time would be a great addition to any raid.  Not having to worry that he’ll die when the first AE hits.
<br />
	
<br />
Now that my fellow mages is impressive.  Not common enough to make old world trivial, but enough that Raid leaders start yelling “More Mages”, and we Mages could sit back with a mug of summoned ale after a raid and congratulate ourselves on a job well done.<br />_________________<br />Elawise Fyremountain</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
